BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Historic Orchard Hike at Jack London State Historic Park
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T090000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T133000
UID:260216mhTwbXPhZEW5ivfFaAHkiw
DESCRIPTION:Take a guided hike to the historic orchard\, now part of Jack 
 London State Historic Park\, and learn about its remarkable restoration. 
  Along the way\, keep an eye out for seasonal wildflowers and perhaps the 
 first delicate blossoms on early blooming fruit trees.\n\nOriginally plant
 ed between 1908 and 1912\, the orchard flourished in Jack London’s time 
 before being abandoned for many years. Today\, thanks to dedicated restora
 tion efforts\, it can once again be enjoyed by all who walk its trails.\n\
 nThe experience begins with an overview presented by Eric Metz\, Director 
 of Operations\, who will share the history of the orchard and the challeng
 es involved in its revival. From there\, participants will hike through re
 dwoods and mixed oak woodlands on a moderate\, six-mile round-trip trek to
  the orchard.\n\n At the orchard\, guests will tour the areas that have b
 een thoughtfully revitalized and learn about unique obstacles overcome in 
 restoring this landscape.
LOCATION:Jack London State Historic Park
URL:https://bohemian.com/events-calendar/#/details/historic-orchard-hike-a
 t-jack-london-state-historic-park/18127751/2026-03-15T09
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Power of Letting Go: Cultivating Well-Being\, Joy\, and Freedo
 m
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T100000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260315T150000
UID:260214ypvC_79so0-0AvqyG6lycQ
DESCRIPTION:with James Baraz\, MA\n\nSpring is a natural time to reflect o
 n what we are holding on to and what may be ready to be released. Just wha
 t does the phrase “let go” mean? Renunciation (*nekkhama* in Pāli)\,
  one of the ten perfections\, is often misunderstood as sacrifice—someth
 ing we should do because it’s “good for us.” In early Buddhist teach
 ings\, *nekkhama* is described not as deprivation\, but as a letting go 
 that supports genuine contentment and well-being\, rooted in seeing more c
 learly what leads to suffering and what leads to freedom.\n\nDuring this d
 aylong program\, which includes periods of guided silent sitting and walki
 ng meditation\, participants will explore how habitual grasping—to thoug
 hts\, personal stories\, possessions\, roles\, and a sense of control—sh
 apes inner experience and contributes to stress. Drawing from contemplativ
 e teachings and incorporating perspectives from psychology on attachment a
 nd habitual mental patterns\, our reflections and practices will focus on 
 meeting these patterns with awareness and kindness\, loosening unhelpful s
 elf-stories\, softening the impulse to control\, and cultivating generosit
 y. This program is educational in nature and welcomes both new and experie
 nced practitioners.
LOCATION:Spirit Rock Meditation Center
URL:https://spirit-rock.secure.retreat.guru/program/the-power-of-letting-g
 o-cultivating-well-being-joy-and-freedom-jb1d26/?lang=en
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
