BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Art Exhibit: Celebrating Women
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260321T110000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260321T180000
UID:2602170KBJi3VAoEiWOkuVXvswbA
DESCRIPTION:Date: FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE  2/13/26\n\n**MARCH EXHIBIT: CELE
 BRATING WOMEN**\n\nEXHIBIT DATES:  February 23 – March 29\, 2026\n\n**R
 ECEPTION: SATURDAY\, MARCH 7\, 2026\, 4-6 pm: Join in to meet the artists 
 and celebrate the show. Take part in the Gallery’s free monthly drawing 
 for a beautiful work by a Gallery artist.  Refreshments will be served.**
 \n\nSonoma County artist\, **Tosya Shore\,** presents **Celebrating Women\
 ,** paintings that commemorate women in honor of Women’s History Month. 
 Shore’s watercolor works capture women in their element\, showing the mu
 ltiple facets of their lives.  These dynamic paintings break away with st
 rong shapes and interlacing patterns that draw the viewer in exciting ways
 .  A la Degas\, we catch a ballet dancer lacing her shoes in “Good Poin
 t.”  The artist takes us into nature with “Redwood Rendezvous” wher
 e dominant trunk shapes frame a couple enjoying a glorious forest scene. 
    “Just Back from Vegas” captures a fleeting view of elegance as th
 e woman in question catches her breath.  “There’s such special feelin
 g in these everyday moments\, I love to turn the mundane into magic – wo
 men deserve nothing less\,” noted Shore. \n\nMeet the artist: Shore wil
 l be hosting the Gallery on March 5 and 19 from 11am to 6 pm.\n\n The Sta
 irway Smallworks Showcase features **Donna Schaffer’s Ooh La La\, Plein 
 Air\,** a collection unveiling oil paintings made on her recent trip to Fr
 ance.  Roaming the streets of Paris\, toting paints and palette\, Schaffe
 r captured iconic scenes buzzing with “la belle vie.” The viewer catch
 es a true cultural vibe in “Café le Bistro”\, the site of a favored h
 angout for espresso and conversation.  One is awed by the structure risin
 g from the ground-level trees in Schaffer’s unique view of the Eiffel To
 wer in “Paris is for Lovers.” “Every day was an adventure in Paris 
 – I hope through these plein air vignettes\, to share the excitement of 
 being there”\, stated Schaffer.\n\nMeet the artist: Schaffer will be hos
 ting the Gallery on March 21 and 22 from 11am to 6 pm.\n\nUpstairs Art Gal
 lery\, 306 Center Street\, Healdsburg\, CA 95448. (707) 431-4214.: OPEN DA
 ILY: 11am – 6 pm.    **www.upstairsart gallery.net** \n\nFor further 
 information: Contact: Beverly Bird\, Press Contact\, at bvdrio@sonic.net o
 r 707-799-1490.
LOCATION:Upstairs Art Gallery
URL:http://www.upstairsartgallery.net
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Japanese Papermaking
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260321T140000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260321T170000
UID:260216ty-_zIJbsUyZ882sfLPjzQ
DESCRIPTION:Schedule\n\nSaturday\, March 21\, 2026 2:00 PM – 5:00 PM Sun
 day\, March 22\, 2026 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM\n\nLocation\n\nRoom 208\n\nExpe
 rience Level\n\nAll Levels\n\nBilingual\, Fiber Arts\, Printmaking\n\nAge\
 \(s\\)\n\n18 and older\n\n$180 – Registration Cost $25 – Materials Fee
  $205 – Total Registration CostLearn traditional Japanese papermaking us
 ing the nagashizuki method. Beat fiber by hand and form delicate\, strong 
 sheets to take home. All levels welcome.\n\nAbout the Class\n\nIn this wor
 kshop\, students will be introduced to the process of making Japanese pape
 r. Japanese paper\, often incorrectly referred to as rice paper\, is known
  for its great strength while appearing delicate and gossamer-thin. In thi
 s workshop\, students will learn the basics of preparing their own fiber\,
  hand beating\, and forming sheets in the traditional nagashizuki method. 
 Students will take home wet sheets to dry at home with instructions. Pleas
 e be aware that papermaking is a wet activity –  wear clothing and shoe
 s that can get wet. Class involves some physical activity\, including stan
 ding and arm movements. All supplies are provided through the materials fe
 e. La maestra habla español. Note: Please bring a bag lunch on Sunday.
LOCATION:Sonoma Community Center
URL:https://sonomacommunitycenter.org/programs/japanese-papermaking/
X-SOURCE:North Bay Bohemian
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Introduction to Pochoir Workshop
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260321T100000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260321T160000
UID:260216TdIDwfpXH0S2ZXczz-hMEA
DESCRIPTION:**Pochoir**\, the French term for stencil\, is a well respecte
 d tradition in book arts. Popular during the late 19th and early 20th cent
 uries\, this art-making technique was an advanced form of stencil printing
 . Artists would apply color pigments to paper by hand as an elegant and af
 fordable way to reproduce artwork in color. Join guest artist\, Bettina Pa
 uly in this exciting one-day introduction to pochoir workshop!\n\nBettina 
 will offer a short history lesson\, and share pochoir samples\, including 
 an artist demonstration on how to use pigments with different applicators.
  Students will be encouraged to learn the basics of stencil creation and w
 ill work on images made up of simple shapes to practice their technique. T
 hroughout the day\, an assortment of materials will be on hand to create s
 tencils\; different brushes and their effects will be examined\; and vario
 us ‘dry pigments’ and papers will be investigated as students expand t
 heir pochoir skills. The instructor will also lead a discussion on how stu
 dents can creatively incorporate pochoir into their own artwork\, includin
 g books\, prints\, cards\, and more!\n\nStudents will work on a set of not
 e cards to take home and learn how to make a simple folder for the samples
  that were made during class. The materials fee will include brushes\, ste
 ncils\, paper pigments and an assortment of paper cardstock.\n\n**Please n
 ote:** This class requires some hand dexterity to maneuver an exacto blade
  cutting knife.
LOCATION:North Bay Letterpress Arts
